		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top" id="forumSubject">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Thu, Mar 31st 8:02 PM2005 </span><span class="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=1112308554113348520&num=11&page=0&post=1&replyto=1112317325333996053"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1112317325333996053></a></small>| <span id="fs8">Edited: 2005-03-31 20:12:09</span></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span class="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=266649"><span id="">Netos</span></a><b><span id=""></span></b><br /><img alt="Avatar" height="67" width="69" src="/uf/Netos/dragon6.gif"><br /><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />127 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.43]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Netos&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%">
<p>Since I started my guild virtually unknown by anyone on the server - I tried out alot of ways to get new recruits.&nbsp;&nbsp;once you establish a bit of a reputation they will start to come to you and you will have to less actual recruiting.  Here's a few that worked well for us - bringing us up to 300 now including alts. <br /> <br />1.  Advertise in PoK (very tacky and the only people that respond are toons below 20 or toons with bad raps with all the other guilds on the server).  These toons seldom last - but it does let people know you exist - just don't spam it.  Typically I would holler in PoK one time - one day out of the week for the first month our guild was up.  After that try the other techniques.  Or just skip this altogether. <br /> <br />2.  Get a website, almost everyone you talk to will ask if you have a website.  A website shows that you intend to stay around awhile and are willing to put a little work into making your guild successful.  Websites allow potential members to see what you have to offer and learn a little bit about the guild without having to ask you or an officer a bunch of questions.  The website doesn't have to be fancy - a message board will do, and many can be found for free. <br /> <br />3.  Send tells to people that are untagged - and of an appropriate level for your guild.  This works best if you are looking for a specific class or level for your guild.  For instance - we were short on mages.  I looked for untagged mages levels 30+ and sent them tells briefly describing our guild and asking if they would be interested, explaining that I was specifically looking for mages to round out our classes.  Be courteous - if they say they aren't interested - say thank you for your time and should you change your mind, here's our website.  Don't randomly pick toons to target - as they will want to know why them, how do you know them, what makes you think they would be a good fit - and not having answers to these questions will make your guild look desperate. <br /> <br />4.  Post a recruiting message on the website for your server if there is one.  For instance, Prexus has a site here:  <a href="http://p199.ezboard.com/fprexus81531frm14" title="http://p199.ezboard.com/fprexus81531frm14" target="akztarg">http://p199.ezboard.com/fprexus81531frm14</a> or check this site - open to all servers: <a href="http://p218.ezboard.com/beqx" title="http://p218.ezboard.com/beqx" target="akztarg">http://p218.ezboard.com/beqx</a> and EQ Live used to have a section too.  Toons new to your server, bored at work, or looking for a guild will check these places and contact you in game if they are interested.  <br /> <br />5.  Form guild groups with 4-5 guildees and then invite someone to fill the last spot or two from the LFG window.  If your group plays well together - the non-guildee should have a good time and may ask about your guild.  A word of caution - if they are already tagged let them ask you about your guild - don't try to recruit toons from other guilds.  This will earn you a bad rep.  This is not a good option if your group dies alot, your guild members do not know how to play their classes well, or they don't get along.  You don't want to air your Guild Drama to a potential recruit. <br /> <br />6.  Ensure your guild members are displaying their tag.  Roleplaying works great for hiding their class/level - Anon does too - but does nothing for your guild.  If your guild members are happy they will do the recruiting for you by talking about things the guild has done, or zones they've recently been too - which leads into the next one. <br /> <br />7.  Plan events/raids.  You don't have to be a big raiding guild to host events for your members.  Our first raid was the Warren's.  We encouraged everyone to bring their lowest level toon and had a great time.  We picked up 3 new members that day that were xping in the Warren's and thought it was cool that a guild would raid there.  PvP competitions and Scavenger hunts work well too for a smaller guild - just don't forget the prizes.  Guild members will invite their friends to come help - or in the case of PvP competitions - to kick their butt.  Our first PvP competion gave us 23 new recruits in one day - mostly friends and family of current members.   <br /> <br />8.  Use the DoN message boards - a new feature so I don't know how well it really works.  But we have gotten 2 new members in the last month that saw us first on the DoN board.  Also, use the board to see who is looking for a guild.  If you think they would like your guild - send them an in-game email or tell if they're on.  I've recruited a few needed classes this way and they've turned out to be great members. <br /> <br />9. Create an application process.  It doesn't have to be real intense, a couple of questions about their goals, and why they want a guild are all you need.  This shows people that you are a little bit picky about who joins - and will show you care about your members and not just the number of toons in your guild.  <br /> <br />There are probably a ton of other ways to recruit out there - the biggest thing to remember is get out there and let toons get to know you and your guild. Also, decide what your goal numbers are - once you reach them, start focusing on getting new members that will work well in your guild and that will stick around. Having a ton of alts is great when you're just getting started but to make it for several months you have to find toons that play and play well.  Your members will do most of the recruiting for you - at least as long as they like their home.   <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Thu Mar 31 20:11:27 2005 by Netos</span></i></p>
<br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br /><a href="HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=887983" title="HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=887983" target="akztarg">Netos Slackerr</a> (66 paladin) <br />Guild Leader of <a href="HTTP://banishedshadows.com" title="HTTP://banishedshadows.com" target="akztarg">Banished Shadows</a> <br />Alts:  <br />Hokto Nogo (47 cleric) <br />Tneo Reo (35 magician)</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from CA</td></tr></table>
