		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span class="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=318851"><span id="">Kcane</span></a><b><span id=""></span></b><br />3 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Kcane&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%">
<p>1) Recruite according to the current levels with-in the guild. Let say you 15 active people between 60 to 70, recruite people with-in that range. <br /> <br />2) Web site is nice to have, but can be very time consuming to maintain. EZ Board.com is the best way to go. Use a message board is simple and low maintance. <br /> <br />3) Like in the real world, this saying applies as well as in EQ. Word of Mouth!!! More you talk about your guild to others, more people see what you are doing. <br /> <br />4) Plan small. Rome wasn't built in a day. Do small raids according to what numbers and classes that are on-line. <br /> <br />Last advice: <br />Look for a quailty player. One who knows his/her class, knows the various zones, understands roles of other classes, and understands and adheres to EQ play nice policy. <br /> <br />Having Patience is the key to being sucessful.</p>
